    <h1>Safety in&#xAD;no&#xAD;va&#xAD;tions to keep work&#xAD;sites safe</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201109/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-11-09"><time>2020-11-09</time></a>
        - <span>PLACE</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>Build­ing In­for­ma­tion Model­ing (BIM)</p>
    <p>BIM is a 3D mod­el­based process al­low­ing com­pa­nies to not only vi­su­alise and plan the con­struc­tion se­quence, but also an­tic­i­pate po­ten­tial haz­ards such as risk of weld­ing in­juries and fall­ing from height.</p>
    <p>Cus­tomised tun­nel-bor­ing ma­chine (TBM)</p>
    <p>Es­sen­tial tools in tun­nelling work like the tun­nel-bor­ing ma­chine can be cus­tomised. Ex­am­ples in­clude adding a sensor to de­tect steel ob­struc­tions and a plasma cut­ter to cut ob­struc­tions. An­other cus­tomised de­sign of tun­nel-bor­ing ma­chine cut­ter-heads is a spe­cial “bolted” joint type in or­der to max­imise the dis­man­tling ef­fi­ciency within tun­nels, min­imise hot works in tun­nels, and avoid sal­vage of cut­ter-head.</p>
    <p>VR train­ing</p>
    <p>Some haz­ards when work­ing un­der­ground in­clude ground loss or de­pres­sion, fire, ex­plo­sion and elec­tro­cu­tion from hit­ting util­ity lines. VR train­ing equips site per­son­nel with the skills to recog­nise dan­ger­ous site-spe­cific sit­u­a­tions with­out the ac­tual risks through im­mer­sive tech­nol­ogy. Site-spe­cific sim­u­la­tions of real work­places and haz­ards in­clude tun­nel safety and emer­gen­cies, con­fined space safety, elec­tri­cal safety and shaft col­lapses.</p>


